3532, \"to\": 3539}, {\"ngram\": \"excrement\", \"from\": 3544, \"to\": 3553}, {\"ngram\": \"tanners' dyes\", \"from\": 3566, \"to\": 3579}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the 19th century, Baron Haussmann and his brigade of engineers and laborers expanded the sewer network, and once-open trenches were hidden underground.\", \"from\": 3590, \"to\": 3744, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3611, \"end\": 3626, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haussmann's_renovation_of_Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.5164333075647571e-43, \"text\": \"Baron Haussmann\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haussmann's_renovation_of_Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haussmann's_renovation_of_Paris\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the 19th century\", \"from\": 3593, \"to\": 3609}, {\"ngram\": \"his brigade\", \"from\": 3631, \"to\": 3642}, {\"ngram\": \"engineers\", \"from\": 3646, \"to\": 3655}, {\"ngram\": \"laborers\", \"from\": 3660, \"to\": 3668}, {\"ngram\": \"the sewer network\", \"from\": 3678, \"to\": 3695}, {\"ngram\": \"once-open trenches\", \"from\": 3701, \"to\": 3719}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But some trenches still disgorged untreated wastewater into the river.\", \"from\": 3745, \"to\": 3815, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"some trenches\", \"from\": 3749, \"to\": 3762}, {\"ngram\": \"untreated wastewater\", \"from\": 3779, \"to\": 3799}, {\"ngram\": \"the river\", \"from\": 3805, \"to\": 3814}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Downstream, where almost 1 million pounds of sewage entered the water each day, the water was reportedly sluggish and black; debris mounded into mud shoals that resisted dredging, as the historian Donald Reid hasnoted.\", \"from\": 3816, \"to\": 4034, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4013, \"end\": 4024, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donald_Reid_Medal\", \"score\": 0.999999998279236, \"rank\": 1.3091982177674626e-09, \"text\": \"Donald Reid\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donald_Reid_Medal\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donald_Reid_Medal\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"almost 1 million pounds\", \"from\": 3834, \"to\": 3857}, {\"ngram\": \"sewage\", \"from\": 3861, \"to\": 3867}, {\"ngram\": \"the water\", \"from\": 3876, \"to\": 3885}, {\"ngram\": \"the water\", \"from\": 3896, \"to\": 3905}, {\"ngram\": \"debris\", \"from\": 3941, \"to\": 3947}, {\"ngram\": \"mud shoals\", \"from\": 3961, \"to\": 3971}, {\"ngram\": \"dredging\", \"from\": 3986, \"to\": 3994}, {\"ngram\": \"the historian\", \"from\": 3999, \"to\": 4012}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the 1870s, theIrish Builder, a trade journal that catered to the engineering-minded,reported thatthe river was laden with liquids from foundries, rubber makers, and laundries-which caused the river to bubble with 132 tons of soap each year-as well as refuse from the process of making poudrette, a fertilizer fashioned from dried excrement.\", \"from\": 4035, \"to\": 4378, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"theIrish Builder\", \"from\": 4049, \"to\": 4065}, {\"ngram\": \"a trade journal\", \"from\": 4067, \"to\": 4082}, {\"ngram\": \"thatthe river\", \"from\": 4131, \"to\": 4144}, {\"ngram\": \"liquids\", \"from\": 4160, \"to\": 4167}, {\"ngram\": \"foundries\", \"from\": 4173, \"to\": 4182}, {\"ngram\": \"rubber makers\", \"from\": 4184, \"to\": 4197}, {\"ngram\": \"laundries\", \"from\": 4203, \"to\": 4212}, {\"ngram\": \"the river\", \"from\": 4226, \"to\": 4235}, {\"ngram\": \"132 tons\", \"from\": 4251, \"to\": 4259}, {\"ngram\": \"soap\", \"from\": 4263, \"to\": 4267}, {\"ngram\": \"the process\", \"from\": 4301, \"to\": 4312}, {\"ngram\": \"poudrette\", \"from\": 4323, \"to\": 4332}, {\"ngram\": \"a fertilizer\", \"from\": 4334, \"to\": 4346}, {\"ngram\": \"dried excrement\", \"from\": 4362, \"to\": 4377}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Well into the 20th century, pollution was blamed for waters goneominously fallow.\", \"from\": 4379, \"to\": 4460, \"entities\": [], \"no